handist.collections

Class LongRange

  • java.lang.Object
    • handist.collections.LongRange
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Comparable<LongRange>, Iterable<Long>

    public class LongRange
extends Object
implements Comparable<LongRange>, Iterable<Long>, Serializable
    Class LongRange describes an interval over long values.

    The lower bound is included and the upper bound is excluded from the interval, meaning that for two long values a and b (a<b), all the long values l such that a ≤ l < b are contained within the LongRange [a,b).

    It is possible to create "empty" LongRange instances where the lower bound is equal to the upper bound. In this case it is considered that there are no long values included in the LongRange.

      • compareTo

        public int compareTo(LongRange r)
        Compares the provided instance to this instance and returns an integer indicating if the provided instance is less than, equal to, or greater than this instance.

        The implementation relies on ordering the lower bounds first before using the ordering of the upper bounds. The implemented ordering of LongRange is consistent with equals. To illustrate the ordering, consider the following examples:

        • [0,0) < [0,100) < [1,1) < [1,20) < [1,21)
        • [0,0) == [0,0)
        • [0,10) == [0,10)

        Specified by:

        Returns:

        NullPointerException - if the instance given as parameter is null

      • isOverlapped

        public boolean isOverlapped(LongRange range)
        Returns true if the provided LongRange and this instance are overlapped. This operation is symmetric, meaning that calling this method with two instances a and b, the result produced by a.isOverlapped(b) is the same as b.isOverlapped(a).

        Two LongRange a and b are overlapped if they share some indices, that is if there exist a long l such that a.contains(l) and b.contains(l) return true.

        In cases where an empty LongRange and a non-empty LongRange are considered, this method returns true if the lower bound (or upper bound as it has the same value) of the empty instance is between the lower bound (included) and the upper bound (excluded) of the other instance.

        If both considered LongRange are empty, returns true if they have the same bounds.

        Parameters:
        range - the range whose overlap with this instance is to be checked
        Returns:
        true if the provided LongRange and this instance overlap
